    <text>
        <body>
            <head>135. Electronic Message From Peter Rodman of the <orgName
                    corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security Council</orgName> Staff to
                    <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s Assistant for
                National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="rec6rjfFsKmuW0bbp"
                    >Poindexter</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d135fn1"
                    >Source: National Archives, PROFS system, <rs type="event"
                        corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si">
                        <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> Administration</rs>.
                    No classification marking. Copied to <persName corresp="recSLgb3bPfEgfMg8"
                        >McDaniel</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1986-06-13T18:02:00-04:00">June 13, 1986, 6:02 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> Meeting with <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> made presentations on two
                issues (<placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> and strategic
                    <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>) and mentioned
                two brief items at the end (<placeName corresp="recrGN6dqTH4MaGw0">Cuba</placeName>
                and <placeName corresp="rec4OxHezeJMPAom9">South Africa</placeName>).<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d135fn2">According to <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                        >the President</persName>’s Daily Diary, <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> met from 1:39–2:16 p.m. in the
                    State Dining Room of the White House. (<persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                        >Reagan</persName> Library, <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                        >President</persName>’s Daily Diary) No memorandum of conversation was
                    found.</note>
            </p>
            <pb facs="0564" n="537" xml:id="pg_537"/>
            <p>[Omitted here is a discussion of the <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle
                    East</placeName>.]</p>
            <p>On <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>, <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> said he wasn’t sure he was
                effectively communicating his view of the issue so he wanted to go over again what
                he had said at the <orgName corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName>.<note n="3"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d135fn3">Minutes of the <orgName
                        corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">National Security Planning Group</orgName>
                    meeting of June 12 are scheduled for publication in <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v05#d243">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. V,
                        Soviet Union, January 1985–October 1986, Document 243</ref>.</note> The key
                aim, he said, was “how to lock in <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>” for succeeding administrations. He felt the Soviets had “reopened the
                bazaar” in both <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> and in conceding <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recJclekZAp3yKmD5">research</rs>. He thought we could live
                with a 5–6 year pledge not to withdraw from the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate"
                    corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">
                    <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss> treaty</rs> since it would be 5–6 years
                until a deployment decision; the Soviets have also said it would take 5–6 years to
                phase in deep <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs>. We could
                match these up, link the two, and “turn <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> into a compliance mechanism that keeps the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> going.” <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The President</persName> said this seemed “akin” to
                what he had said at the <orgName corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName>: Both
                sides could keep on with <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recJclekZAp3yKmD5">research</rs> and, at the moment of a
                deployment decision, share the knowledge, observe each other’s tests, and deploy
                based on the elimination of <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. A treaty to this effect would lock <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> in. <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> interpreted
                this as consistent with what he had said, and told <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> he was “reassured” by this
                conversation. I made no comment, but told <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                    >Shultz</persName> afterwards that you too thought these concepts could be
                merged and that you would have a paper next week.</p>
            <p>[Omitted here is a discussion of topics not related to <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>]</p>
        </body>
